{
  "text": "Most of what we know about the role of the DDR in HPV biology has been elucidated from studies of late viral DNA replication. The E1 and E2 replication proteins are induced to high levels by a differentiation-dependent induction of the late promoter [CITATION_1] and this coincides with activation of a DDR [CITATION_2] . Many studies have also shown that E1 can specifically upregulate and contribute to the activation of the DDR in non-differentiated cells, and when coexpressed with E2, many DDR factors such as pATM, pATR, \u03b3H2AX, pChk2, pChk1, BRCA1, RAD51, TopBP1 and pNBS1 colocalize within nuclear foci that replicate viral DNA to high levels [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "19698526",
    "[CITATION_2]": "16486535",
